<statement>
<p>Graph the parabola <m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left({x}+{2}\right)}^{{2}}+{3}</m></p>
<p>The vertex is <fillin characters="7" /> Â </p>
<image width="52%"  pi:generated="problems/images/2b9e9c42125647599d5eba4968563ef1.png" />


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{2},{3}\right)}</m></li><li><image width="52%"  pi:generated="problems/images/0415b0612968db0fc3d4a9c17a53ab31.png" />
</li></ul></p><p>The form of a parabola is <m>\displaystyle{y}={a}{\left({x}-{h}\right)}^{{2}}+{k}</m>. Because this parabola is <m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left({x}+{2}\right)}^{{2}}+{3}</m>, which can be written <m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left({x}-{\left(-{2}\right)}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left({3}\right)}</m> we know the following.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{h}=-{2}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{k}={3}</m>. Thus the vertex is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{2},{3}\right)}</m>.</p>
<p>To graph the parabola we can use the vertex and another convenient point. One convenient point is at <m>\displaystyle{x}=-{2}+{1}=-{1}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left(-{1}-{\left(-{2}\right)}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left({3}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle={6}{\left({1}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left({3}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle={6}+{\left({3}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle={9}</m>.</p>
<p>We use <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{1},{9}\right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
